That's not necessarily true. People might have similar ideas and one just executes it better so they went with the better writer/content. We've been looking for someone to do flavor articles and while there are others out there and some have come to us, it's not proprietary unless you're using the exact name. How many budget writers have we had come through the site? Or "this commander is underplayed!" articles.

If someone that we turned down for a flavor article came out and said "I submitted an idea to you months ago and now you have a new flavor writer! This is a rip off!" I'd have trouble buying that we did anything wrong. Maybe their execution wasn't good?

Emotionally going after someone publicly when you're trying to get them to publish your content is rarely going to look good, especially for other content producers that might pickup that mantle they declined.

Is just submitting their ideas to another site and just not worrying about the original one an option? If they still want to write because they enjoy it, then pitching it somewhere else is the next best move right?
Yeah, I was just about to say that Matt. People might not want to work with someone if they’re going to call them out for rejecting their content.

Something more productive than putting the site on blast for "totes ripping off my idea" would be reaching out directly to the site that turned you down and ask for feedback on why, what you could do to improve the idea and if they would be open to a more refined product.
